Coach chose his nephew over me and I got to see the nepotism backfire. My coach told me that they were not bringing me in for the next season. What he didn't mention was that I'd been his starting point guard for three years, team captain since junior year. My whole future depended on those three games. I even got my Jersey number tattooed on my shoulder, 23, the same number my dad wore when he played. But when Coach Miller called me into his office that Monday morning, he couldn't even look me in the eye, just stared at his desk, shuffling the same papers over and over, clicking his pen repeatedly like he always did when he was nervous. My nephew, Keith just transferred from Preston Prep. He needs stability right now. I just nodded quietly even though my chest felt like it was caving in. Whatever's best for the team, I said. He seemed shocked I wasn't arguing. Probably expected me to beg, maybe cry like Johnson did when he got cut last year. Instead, I cleaned out my locker in complete silence, folded my practice gear with the same precision I used for my pre game rituals. My Jersey hanging on the hook, the one with the captain's patch my mom had sewn on herself. Keith was already in the gym wearing my number, running my plays, using my parking spot. That afternoon I drove across town to our biggest rival school, hands shaking the whole Way their star player had just torn his knee at a party trying to dunk on a lowered rim. Coach Thompson nearly fell over when I walked in. You serious? He asked, already reaching for transfer paperwork before I even finished explaining. Two days later, I was practicing with my new team, wearing No. 5 because my number was already taken. Strange faces, different plays, but hungry eyes that reminded me why I love basketball. First game in the new uniform, I played the best game of my life against the defending state champions, the same team that had destroyed us.

What's the worst announcement your school ever made? I was halfway through my sandwich when the old speakers buzzed loudly. They always did before an announcement, but this time it didn't sound like the lunch schedule. Principal's voice came on, but it was shaky. Attention, students, everyone must return to their classrooms immediately and lock the doors. This is not a drill. The lunch lady stopped serving and I looked at my friends and they looked at me and then we all moved at once. By the time we got to class, our teacher was already closing the blinds. She locked the door behind us and told us to move our desks to the corner away from the windows. Nobody said anything, but everyone was thinking the same thing, there was a shooter. A few minutes later, we heard sirens and then screaming. Our teacher tried to calm us down and told us it might be a misunderstanding, but her hands were shaking, kept refreshing the email on her laptop like it was giving her live updates. Then we heard a loud pop from the hallway, like a metal slamming or something crashing hard. People started crying and whispering that they were right outside and I believe them. I looked at our teacher and for the first time in my life, I saw her cry. She sat with us, hugged the younger kids and told us it would be okay. But after a while, she got up again and walked. Back to her laptop. Then something changed because her face went pale. She looked at me and asked if there was a Jack Arthur in here. The whole class turned to me like I was in trouble. She asked me to come to her and whispered if I had anything in the room that belonged to me. And I told her just my backpack. She told me to grab it and wait by the door. I didn't understand what was happening, so I waited. Few minutes later, there was a knock and the teacher opened the door and told me to go with the officer. Outside the hallway was full of cops and medics. I thought maybe I was being arrested and tried to think what I did wrong. But then I saw the soda machine near the bathrooms tipped over and next to it a shoe and a leg sticking out. The officer stepped in front of me fast and told me to keep my eyes forward, but I'd already seen it. He took me to a side room and told me to wait. Then the door opened and my uncle walked in. He lives an hour away and he never comes to school. So I asked him if I was in trouble but told me I was safe. I asked about my little brother Timmy, but he didn't answer. Instead, he told me I needed to be strong for him. But I didn't understand. He asked me to Wear a blindfold and told me.

Punished my son for colouring his nails and he hasn't talked to me for a whole year. I care about my teenage boy, but I'd be dishonest if I said I wasn't let down by the kind of person he's becoming. My son began getting into this different look back when he was in middle school. At first he just wore black clothes, but once he got to high school, he's gone way too far with his strange style and I really don't like it. My wife doesn't seem to mind, but she's a pretty passive woman and has never been a very strict parent like me. If I were to describe how my son dresses now, he wears big, baggy black clothing and lots of chains and rings. At one point, he was even dying coloured strips into his hair. I remember being so upset the first day I saw this. It was just so embarrassing to see my child walking around like that. Now, I don't have a problem with gay people or anything like that, but I never really wanted that type of thing to be a part of my own household. I've never confronted my son about his sexuality and I really just don't wanna know if he does happen to be. Our relationship is already sort of strained and I feel like if I found out he wasn't straight, it would make it very hard for me to treat him the same. Like I said, I don't have a problem with gay people. I just don't wanna be shoved in my face on top of everything. Ever since my son entered high school, he's made friends with mostly girls. At first I was glad to see this, and I was happy that my son still might have a chance of growing up into a real man's man. But as time went on, I realized that he wasn't in a relationship with any of these girls dead. They were all just his close friends. He constantly has his friends over the house and is part of a friend group with three other girls. To be fair, these girls have always been nothing but polite to me and my wife and are always respectful of our house. Still, it just rubs me the wrong way that my son doesn't seem to have any close guy friends. And I feel like it's not good for him to grow up that way. I tried my best to be non judgmental towards my son, even though to me he looked like more of a freak of nature. Every day the more he kept leaning into his alternative fashion. I didn't understand it, since all of his friends were normal girls. He was the only weirdo in his friend group who dressed like some 90s mall rat. When I look at him, he honestly reminds me of the kind of kids I would pick on in high school. Anyway, about a Year ago, I ran out of patience with him when he came home one day with his nails painted a shade of bright blue. My son had never done anything like this before, and I couldn't help but feel overwhelmingly disgusted. I told him that he had gone too far with his emo bullshit and that I couldn't continue letting him make a fool out of himself like this. I told him that at one point he needed to become a man, and painting his nails made him look like some sort of weak top. My son and I had never really been close. We didn't even speak that often, so he looked very hurt as I was telling him all this. But I couldn't help it. He had needed a reality check for so long and there was no avoiding this conversation. I told my son to go get nail polish remover and remove his nail polish right there in front of me. That's when he started to get angry and said that he didn't have to change himself just to appease my dumb, homophobic son. My son has never spoken to either of his parents this way, and I knew that there was no way I was letting him get away with it. I yelled at him for cursing at me like that, and I told him that he would remove his nail polish immediately or there would be serious consequences. He said that there was nothing worse. I could do to him than continue being such a hateful father. And that's when I lost my shot. I told him that I would ground him for the entire year if he didn't remove his nail polish within the next 60 seconds. Looked at me and told me that I could try, but I would never be able to control him and that he hated me. He ran up to his room after this, and I followed through on my threat. I took his phone away and replaced it with a flip phone, and he wasn't allowed to go out or have his friends over anymore. All he did after that for the rest of the year was call his friends in his room and completely ignore me. One night, I overheard him crying to my wife about how much he hated his life since being grounded. But all she said was that I was his father and he needed to respect me. Proud of my wife for sticking up to me behind closed doors. And I still felt like I had made the right decision. I won't lie and say that it hasn't been a difficult year. My son stopped talking to me the day I grounded him, and I honestly do miss him. He graduates next year, and I just hope before then he'll realise that I was only ever trying to do what was best for him.

Ever heard my girlfriend say he's going to propose tonight, watch me say no and make him cry? I still took her to the rooftop, got down on one knee, then pulled out her texts with her gym buddy and said loudly, actually, I'm not proposing. I'm here to say goodbye in front of everyone you tried to impress. This happened 3 weeks ago and I'm still processing it. My girlfriend Danielle and I had been together for 3 years. I've been dropping engagement hints constantly, showing me rings, talking about weddings. I've been secretly saving for months, even picked out a ring. The plan was to propose at her company's rooftop holiday party. She kept mentioning how romantic it would be with the City Lights and all her co workers there. But last Tuesday changed everything. I came home early from my hospital shift. I heard Danielle on Facetime upstairs laughing. Melissa, he's definitely doing it at the party tomorrow. He's been acting all secretive. I stopped on the stairs. That's exciting. Are you ready? Her sister asked. Here's the thing, I'm saying no right in front of everyone. My blood went cold. Danielle, what? Why? He needs a reality check. Plus, you know Anthony from Crossfit. He just started his own business. Way more ambitious than a nurse. Anthony, the guy she'd been training with three nights a week. You're really going to humiliate him at your work party? Picture this, all my co workers watching. He gets Down on one knee and I just say sorry. But no, maybe he'll understand. He can't coast through life helping sick people all day. They both giggled. I quietly went to my car and sat there for an hour. That night, Danielle was all over me. Babe, I love you so much. All I could think about was her planning my destruction. Wednesday morning, her phone buzzed with a text from Anthony. Can't wait to celebrate tomorrow. She'd left it unlocked. I scrolled through their messages. So, so tomorrow's the big day, Anthony had written. Yep, poor guy has no idea what's coming. You sure you wanna do this at work? Seems harsh. He needs this wake up call. Besides, I'll need someone to comfort me after. Always here for you. Can't wait to see his face. Weeks of messages like this. I took screenshots. That afternoon, Danielle called me bouncing with excitement. Tom, I can't wait for tonight. Everyone's going to be there. My boss, the whole team. It's going to be perfect. Perfect for my public destruction. Can't wait, I said. The party was on the 40th floor with incredible downtown views. Danielle Network introduced me as my boyfriend, Tom. He's a nurse. Like she was embarrassed. Anthony showed up around eight PM, big guy, Crossfit shirt, giving me this smug look. Around 9:30, Danielle got antsy, checking her phone constantly. The view is incredible. My daughter shaving her sister's head in her sleep the night before prom was the best thing she ever did. I woke up to my teenage daughter Kayla's piercing screams. Prom was in 8 hours and she was supposed to be a shoe in for Queen. Now it was ruined. Where's Reese, I demanded. And my husband found her sitting on her own bed in her unicorn pajamas with his electric razor on her nightstand. Reese, what did you do? I asked, trying not to scream while Kayla sobbed in the bathroom. I had to stop her from going to prom, Reese said in that small voice she uses when she knows she's in trouble but thinks she did the right thing. This was my baby, who still crawled into Kayla's bed during thunderstorms. The same little girl who Kayla taught to ride a bike last summer, the one who followed her big sister everywhere, asking endless questions about everything. I couldn't believe she would sabotage her sister's big night like this. Before I could respond, the doorbell rang. Kayla's boyfriend, Steven, let himself in like he always did on Saturday mornings. He came Upstairs calling about corsage colours and stopped dead when he saw Kayla's bald head. What the hell happened to your hair, he asked and quickly rearranged his face into concern. Baby, don't cry. We can fix this. Maybe get you a nice wig. You'll still be the prettiest girl there. Kayla was crying harder now. Steven pulled her against him while glaring at me like this was my fault. Did Reese do this? I always said that kid was weird. This is assault, Missus Adams. Reese appeared in the bathroom doorway still in her unicorn pajamas. I cut off all her hair so she couldn't go to prom with you because you're mean to her, Reese, I yelled. But she kept talking in that determined little kid voice. You hurt my sister all the time, Kevin. I see the purple marks on her arms where you grabbed her too hard. The bathroom went silent. Steven laughed, but it sounded forced. Kids make up crazy stories. Missus Adams, tell her, Kayla, tell your mom how good I am to you. Kayla wouldn't look at anyone. I felt ice spreading through my chest. I took pictures on Mommy's phone. When Kayla was sleeping, Reese said, her voice getting stronger. You push her into walls. You hit her tummy where nobody can see. Then you buy her presents after so she won't tell. I pulled out my phone with shaking hands and opened my photos. There they were, close UPS of Kayla's arms. With finger shaped bruises, her ribs with dark purple marks. I felt my stomach drop. Oh, my god, I whispered. Kayla, is this true? Steven's face was getting red. Those could be from anything she plays.

Apples, berries, anything that would ferment. Pretty soon I was making mead too, and even figured out how to malt grain to make beer since the nearest homebrew shop was literally thousands of miles away. Yeah, we lived in a weird spot. Anyway, my stuff turned out pretty decent. Clear, balanced, strong enough to get the job done. Nothing fancy, but it worked. Word got around fast because nobody had any other options. People started trading me things for bottles. my neighbor gave me fresh eggs every week for a case of apple wine. Another guy fixed my fence for some mead. It was honestly a pretty sweet setup and kept everyone happy during a really boring time. But this one guy in our group, let's call him Brian, absolutely hated that I was doing this. He made wine too, but his was honestly not great. It was drinkable. I Guess, but nothing special. The thing that really got under his skin was that people actually wanted mine. At parties, everyone would drink my stuff and his bottles would just sit there mostly untouched. His wife would always try to hype up his wine, too, which made it even more awkward. Brian started making comments every single time we hung out. If I brought wine to someone's house, he'd make a face and say something like, oh, you brought the battery acid? Or trying to poison us again, huh? At first I laughed it off because whatever, dude, more for everyone else. But he kept going. Every gathering, every tasting night, every time someone mentioned my wine, he had something negative to say. His wife backed him up too, which I thought was weird. Like she'd agree and say things like, yeah, Brian's wine is so much smoother, even when she'd barely touched his own bottles. It became this whole thing where they'd team up to trash talk my brewing whenever they got the chance. One night we organized a big tasting event at someone's house. Basically, everyone brought whatever they've been making or bought, and we'd all sample and talk about it. It was supposed to be chill and fun. I brought a few different batches I've been working on, including one I was actually pretty proud of. Brian showed up with his wife and immediately started his usual routine, but this time I was ready see a few Weeks before this, he'd asked me for some tips on his brewing process because one of his batches had turned out especially bad. I helped him out, and he ended up with a decent bottle for once. He gave me one to try, and honestly, it wasn't terrible. I kept it. So at this tasting, I poured everyone samples from different unmarked bottles. I labeled them with numbers instead of names, so people could judge them blind without knowing who made what. Brian

I kicked my family off my Amazon plan. So my whole family had been using my Amazon Prime account for like three years. My mom, my sister Ashley, my Uncle Rick. Even my grandma somehow figured out how to order stuff. I was paying for it because I actually use Amazon all the time for work stuff and groceries, but they were just leeching off it. The breaking point happened two weeks ago. I check my account and see 17 packages coming to different addresses. 17! My sister ordered a whole workout set she'll never use. My mom got some fancy face cream that cost 60 bucks, and my Uncle Rick ordered a drone he definitely doesn't need. But the worst part was my cousin Blake ordered a gaming chair that cost $400. I called Blake and asked him what the hell he was thinking. He just laughed and said it's not his problem. I gave everyone access, said if I didn't want people using it, I shouldn't have shared the password. This kid just graduated high school and acts like he runs the world. So I called my mom and told her everyone needed to chip in for prime or get their own accounts. She got all dramatic and said family should help each other out. She reminded me how she used to buy me clothes when I was younger. I told her that was literally her job as a parent and not the same thing at all. Then Ashley calls me crying, saying she can't afford her own prime account because she's saving for a wedding. I reminded her that her wedding is in two years and she just spent $300 on workout clothes she returned last month. She said I was being petty and that it's only like $10 a month split between everyone. I did the math. If everyone chipped in 10 bucks, that would actually cover prime and give me extra money. But when I suggested this in our family group chat, suddenly everyone had excuses. My mom said she's on a fixed income. Ashley said she's saving for the wedding. Rick said he barely uses it anyway, which is a lie because he ordered protein powder just yesterday. The final straw was when my grandma called me, confused about why her soap order got cancelled. Turns out my account got flagged for suspicious activity. Because there were so many different addresses, Amazon temporarily locked my account and I couldn't order my medication refills. That's when I snapped. I changed the password and removed everyone's.

Did faking sick to skip school go too far? I used to fake sick at least once a month. Nothing dramatic, just your classic ugh, my stomach hurts routine. I'd shuffle into the kitchen, wrap myself in a blanket, throw in a little cough, and wait for my mom to sigh and say, fine, but no video games. She always fell for it. Or maybe she just didn't care enough to argue. This time felt no different. It was a Thursday. I had a math test I wasn't ready for, and zero energy to sit through Mr. Danner's forty five minute rant about fractions, so I pulled out the old stomachache move. My mom was already halfway out the door for work, so she just nodded and left. I grabbed a bowl of cereal, flopped on to the couch, and turned on some cartoons, already feeling like I'd won. Dad works nights, so he usually sleeps through most of the day and the house stays quiet, but around 10:00 I heard his door open. I muted the TV and listened. He walked past the living room without noticing me, phone in hand, and stepped out into the garage. Didn't think much of it at first, figured maybe he was calling in sick or trying to get a refund for something. But then I heard his voice through the wall. And it wasn't his normal voice. It was quiet, tired, flat. I can't do this anymore, he said. I paused. I Tried. I really tried. But I feel like I don't even know my family anymore. I come home and everything's just cold. I tiptoed down the hall, heart suddenly racing. The garage door was cracked open, just like always, and I crouched beside it. I know this isn't what we wanted, but it's where we are now, he said. Every day I feel like I'm just pretending. Pretending to be fine. Pretending to be a good husband, a good dad. My stomach twisted. This time for real. I mean, look at him, he said. He doesn't even like me. He doesn't talk to me unless he wants something. And when he does, it's just one word. Answers. I don't even know who he is anymore. My throat went dry. I look at him and all I can think is, what happened? What did I do wrong? When did he start looking at me like I was a stranger? There was silence then. It was summer from my English class, a pregnant senior who everyone whispered about but nobody really talked to. She was sitting on the toilet, gripping the handicap rail with white knuckles, and her face was covered in sweat. What's wrong? I asked, even though I was starting to guess. Please do something. I'm giving birth. She looked up at me with pure terror in her eyes. My whole body went cold. I was 17 and barely knew how tampons worked, let alone babies. But she was crying and alone, and I couldn't just leave her there. I hopped over the stall divider awkwardly and almost slipped on the wet floor. That's when I saw it. The baby was already crowning. There was blood on the toilet seat and the floor, and summer was making the low groaning sounds that scared me more than anything. This was actually happening in a gross school bathroom with fluorescent lights and graffiti on the walls. I'll be right back. I ran out of the bathroom. Still in shock. I sprinted down the hallway to Missus Bashar's classroom. She was my favourite teacher and The only adult I could think of who wouldn't freak out, I burst through her door, interrupting her lecture on photosynthesis. The whole class stared at me. I need your help urgently, please. I was out of breath and probably looked insane. Missus Bashar took one look at my face and followed me without asking questions. We ran back to the bathroom and I could hear summer sounds getting louder. Other kids were starting to peek out of classrooms wondering what was happening. Missus Bashar pushed open the stall door and immediately went into teacher mode. Okay, honey, I'm here. You're doing great. I'm going to support you while she gets the nurse. I didn't need to be told twice. I ran to the nurse's office faster than I'd ever run in PE. When I burst through the door, Nurse Patty was checking Casey's temperature. Casey, who everyone knew was Summer's boyfriend, the guy who'd been bragging about becoming a dad at prom. Summer's having her baby in the bathroom right now. I basically screamed it. Casey's face went from white to green. He threw up all over the floor before Nurse Patty could grab a trash can. But we didn't have time to deal with that. The three of us ran back to the bathroom with nurse Patty grabbing emergency supplies from her cabinet. By now, half the school had heard something was happening. Kids were crowding outside the bathroom door trying to figure out what all the screaming Was about teachers were trying to move them back to class, but nobody was listening. When we got back to the stall, it was chaos. Missus Bashar was holding Summer's hand while she pushed. The nurse immediately took over, checking how dilated she was and telling summer to breathe. Casey stood frozen in the doorway looking like he might pass out. That's when summer grabbed my hand and pulled me close. You have to get.

voice_to_text: Miguel, it's crazy here. Where did you write down how to make Antonio's plate? Carlos is freaking out. I texted back, everything should be in the kitchen somewhere. There's nothing here. Just the regular menu recipes. Of course, there wasn't anything written down. All those special orders lived in my head, like Don Roberto's Saturday special with my secret salsa blend that took me three years to perfect. Or Maria's eggs with that specific combination of peppers she'd been ordering for 15 years. I knew exactly how much of each spice to use, which vendors sold the best chilies and how every regular like their tortillas toasted. At 8:30, Elena called me directly. Miguel, Don Roberto's whole family is here for their monthly gathering, 12 people, and they all want their usual orders. Roberto's asking for you specifically. I wish I could help, I said. And I really meant it because I like Don Roberto and his family. By 9:00am, owner Rosa Herrera called begging me to come back for triple pay. But I told her I'd already started at Lupita's Kitchen down the street. Elena texted that Don Roberto waited exactly 20 minutes before standing up with his entire 12 person family and announcing they were going to find wherever Miguel's cooking now. And within an hour, half the breakfast crowd had followed them to Lupita's. At noon, Carlos called accusing me of sabotage and theft. Those recipes are company property. What? Those were my creations from 12 years. Made with spices I bought myself and notes in my personal notebook. He threatened to sue, but I told him to check with Rosa about what belonged to the company and he hung up. That afternoon, Carlos posted on Facebook about exciting standardized menu improvements, but comments destroyed him, with customers asking where I went and saying they'd never come back. One lady wrote her mother had been coming for 30 years and Saturday was her first walk out. Monday, I was officially at Lupitas with a 45% raise plus a share of breakfast sales. Thursday, Elena texted that Carlos got fired after Rosa discovered he'd been stealing by lying about food costs and the community center switched their catering to Lupitas. Friday morning, Don Roberto sat at his new regular table while I served his Saturday special with extra jalapenos Miguel, he said with a big smile, this tastes just like it should.

voice_to_text: My sister mocked me for being adopted, so I made our parents wish they'd picked me twice. Growing up, Haley never missed a chance to remind me I wasn't real family. Every sibling fight ended the same way. At least my parents actually wanted me from the start, instead of getting stuck with leftovers. It stung every single time. Our parents loved me. I knew that. But Haley's words planted seeds of doubt. Was I really chosen, or was I just convenient? When I was 15, something shifted. I overheard mom and dad talking about how they wish they could connect better with different cultures, especially after watching a Korean drama together. Mom sighed and said, I wish I could speak another language. It would open up so many conversations. That's when I got my idea. I started learning Korean in secret. Every night after homework, I'd use language apps with headphones. I found online tutor and told my parents the money was for school projects. I watched K dramas without subtitles, practice pronunciation until my jaw ached. Even started cooking Korean recipes I found online during weekends when everyone was out. Meanwhile, Haley was busy dating Daniel, this guy she met at community college. She'd constantly brag about how cultured and worldly he was because he'd spent a semester in Europe. She'd make snotty comments like, some people are naturally interesting, others are just basic, always looking right at me when she said it. What made it worse was That our parents seemed impressed by Daniel, too. They'd ask him about his travels, his experience, princes treating him like he was this sophisticated addition to our family dinners. Daniel was actually pretty nice to me, but Haley would always cut our conversation short. Don't bore him with your random interests, she say, rolling her eyes. The perfect opportunity came during Haley's graduation party from community college. She'd invited Daniel and insisted he bring his parents, who had immigrated from Korea when he was young. She wanted to show off her international boyfriend's family to all our relatives. But when Daniel's parents arrived, everything went sideways. My fiance's best friend accidentally sent me a text meant for her. Did you tell him about Vegas yet? Lol. I responded, Vegas, tell me more. What she confessed next made me cancel the wedding during her bachelorette party. We've been together 4 years. Engaged one. The venue was locked. Caterer paid, dress fitted. She left Thursday for her bachelorette weekend. She and her bridesmaids. Laughter in the air, champagne flutes ready. Everything seemed perfect until Friday. Did you tell him about Vegas yet? Lol. I stared at my phone. Vegas. She went to Vegas 6 months ago for a work conference. Nothing ever about Vegas yet. But I played along. Vegas, tell me more. Three dots appeared. Stay, disappeared, stayed again. Then my phone rang. It was Jenna, her maid of honor. Her voice high, nervous. Tom, I meant to text Kayla. It's nothing. Just a joke about that conference. I said. We're getting married tomorrow. If there's something I should know about Vegas, now's the time. Silence. Can we meet? I can't do this over text. We met at a coffee shop downtown. Kayla had ducked out of party prep. Jenna sat, shaking face pale, tears in her eyes. The guilt's been eating me, she said. What happened in Vegas? She leaned forward. It wasn't just a conference extend. Kayla met up with her ex, Dimitri. They hooked up. Worse, they got married. My gut dropped. Married as in legal. Jenna showed me a photo. Kayla in a White dress, not a wedding gown. But in a small chapel, standing beside Dimitri, they were married. Legal, Jenna stammered. We were drunk, thought it was a joke, but it was legal. She tried to get it annulled quietly. She said it would be handled before your wedding. So she wanted me to marry a woman who's already married. She told me she would finalize it after your wedding. She wanted you to believe the paperwork was done so no one would know. I barely heard her. My mission was set. I left the coffee shop. I drove to the Ritz where the bachelorette party was going full swing. Laughter, music, champagne. I knocked. Tori, Kayla's sister, answered, glass in hand. Tips. Tom, you can't be here. Boys aren't allowed. I squared my shoulders. We need to talk now. Kayla appeared behind her in a sash and tiara. Her face drained. What are you doing here? I said, Vegas, Dimitri, the chat.

Am I the a hole for calling the police immediately when my sister's family broke into my new house with a stolen spare key? I, twenty seven f, have spent my entire life playing second fiddle to my sister Anna. 30th. She's always been the golden child. Growing up, Anna got princess parties with ponies. I got frozen pizza and a cake from Walmart. She got new toys, I got knock offs with pieces missing. Her college fully funded mine. I had to pay rent to live at home while working a $9 per hour job and studying computer science. Every time I asked why she got help and I didn't. You're independent. You'll figure it out. So I did. I skipped meals, borrowed textbooks, and still graduated with a 3.9 GPA. No Celebration, just another night at home like nothing happened. Meanwhile, Anna graduated with a 3.2 and got a catered party with a DJ and champagne toasts. I stopped sharing my life with them. Especially when I started house hunting. I knew the second they found out, they'd find a way to make it about Anna. And they did. A coworker accidentally let it slip that I was looking. Within days, my mom called all fake cheerful. Kate, we've been looking at houses for you. You'll need at least four bedrooms for the kids when they visit, and maybe a pool. I don't have kids. They meant Anna's kids. Then the link started. Every day. Giant Homes with five bedrooms, yards, extra rooms for Josh's office or space for mom and dad to visit. Anna even sent me one that said this would finally give us room to breathe. Us. I stopped responding, silenced the group chat, finished closing on a house by myself. A quiet two bedroom cottage outside the city. It wasn't big, but it was mine. Kitchen, cozy porch, garden in the back. I didn't tell them a thing. Then came the family dinner. I showed up, sat through fake small talk, knowing something was coming. Sure enough, after the lasagna, mom pulled out her phone like she was announcing a real estate deal. We found the perfect place. Five bedrooms? Yes! Sweet. And it's only a few blocks from Anna's. I set my fork down and said, I already bought a house. Silence. Anna stared at me. Wait, what? A two bedroom? Where are we supposed to stay? You're not. Boom! Mom lost it. How could you make such a huge decision without us? We've been helping you. No, I said you've been house shopping for Anna, not for me.

My daughter saved for eight months to buy a bike. Then her piggy bank was suddenly empty. I went to grab some quarters from my daughter's piggy bank for parking and found nothing but three pennies rolling around inside. Layla was only seven and had been saving up for months to buy a new bike with all her birthday and tooth fairy money. The piggy bank felt way too light when I picked it up, and those three pennies made this sad little noise when I shook it. When Layla got home from school, I sat her down at the kitchen table with her favourite snack. Sweetie, where did all your piggy bank money go? She kept her eyes on her shoes and mumbled something I couldn't hear. What was that, honey? I asked gently. I gave it all to Aubrey, she finally said louder. She never has lunch money, and yesterday the lunch lady didn't let her eat. My heart swelled with pride, but I was also confused. Why didn't this kid have lunch money? The next morning, I gave Layla five extra dollars. Give this to Aubrey for lunch today, okay? She jumped up and threw her arms around me. Thanks, Mommy. You're the best, she said, before running to catch the bus. I couldn't stop thinking about why some kid didn't have lunch money every single day. Because as even when money was tight, we always figured it out. Around lunchtime, my phone rang. This is Principal Rouse, could you come in for a meeting about Layla? Twenty minutes later, I was sitting in the principal's office. Your daughter has been giving money to another student, which is technically against school policy, but we need to talk about the whole situation here. I braced myself. Aubrey's family has been going through a lot. We can't share all the details, but your daughter has been making sure that child eats lunch every day. She paused and looked at me carefully. The family applied for free lunch, but there's a waiting period and tons of paper.

Have you ever been recruited to be Santa's helper at a mall by a desperate elf? Last December I was killing time at the mall, waiting for my girlfriend to finish her shift at the jewelry store, when a tiny woman in an elf costume grabbed my arm. Please, please, you have to help me, she whispered, her fake pointed ears drooping. Santa just quit mid shift and there are 40 kids in line. I'm 6 foot 4 with a beard I've been growing since October. She looked at me like I was the answer to her prayers. I don't know anything about being Santa, I protested. She was already dragging me toward the North Pole set up. Can you say ho ho, ho and not swear in front of children? When I nodded, she said, you're hired. Before I could object, she shoved me into a break room where a red suit hung on a chair, still warm from the previous Santa. He left because kid threw up on him, she explained, tossing me the pants. Third time this week. I should have run, but she looked so desperate, and somewhere outside, children were waiting. The suit was too small, the jacket barely closed, the pants ended at my calves, and the beard kept sliding sideways. The elf, who introduced herself as Brenda, looked me over and sighed. It'll have to do. Just remember, every kid gets a candy cane. No promises about specific gifts. Absolutely no holding babies. My First kid was easy, a shy five year old who whispered she wanted a Dinosaur. I deepened my voice, said something about checking my list, and sent her off with a candy cane. I thought I had this figured out. Then came Tyler. Tyler was seven, skeptical, and armed with questions. Why does your beard smell like coffee? He demanded. How do you fit down chimneys if you're so fat? Before I could answer, he pulled my beard down and announced to the entire line, this isn't the real Santa! Panic spread through the crowd. Parents glared, children started crying. Brenda

Days later, her brother Julian showed up at my office. You've got her engagement ring. Mom wants it back today. The ring was conditional upon marriage. The condition is no longer being met. That ring's worth more than your car. We can make this unpleasant. Are you threatening me? I asked calmly. Phone recording in plain sight. Give back the ring, give Isabel her furniture half and apologize publicly. No. The ring's in secure storage. She can have furniture if she pays moving costs. And I won't apologize for being dumped by a text. That evening, I drove to storage with a sickening feeling. My grandfather's desk had a secret. The compartment I'd shown Isabelle. Once. I opened it empty. My grandfather's watch. Gone. She'd stolen it before I'd even started packing. The one thing truly irreplaceable to me. I'd mistaken my calm for weakness. Fine. They'd get a war fought. With receipts and documentation, I filed small claims for the stolen watch, camera, laptop and Isabel's share of final rent. Court day arrived. I wore a simple suit with one organized folder. They arrived as a phalanx. Marcus, Eleanor, Isabel and Julian. I presented simply. Here's the list. Bills, receipts, photo of me wearing my grandfather's watch. And the text that started it all. I read it aloud. I'm not marrying A broke man. Either upgrade or I'm gone. Marcus argued the items were gifts. Text was hyperbole. I was vindictive. The judge looked at Isabel. Did you take the watch from the desk? Her eyes flickered to her mother. It was a gift. Is that true, sir? No, your honor. It was my grandfather's. Priceless to me. She ruled in my favor on all counts. They were ordered to return everything and pay the watches value plus outstanding rent. Julian had to physically restrain Marcus from yelling at the judge. A week later, a courier delivered the camera, laptop, and a check. Oh, note, I sold the ring and used it as down payment on a condo. A real upgrade. Months later, Isabel texted at 2 a m. Heard you bought a condo. Guess my little push worked. You should thank me. I deleted it without replying.

What's a lesson you had to learn the hard way? When I was broke in college, my roommate's cousin Kevin offered me what seemed like the easiest job ever. Manage an online clothing store's Instagram. Post pictures, reply to comments, copy paste stuff. 300 bucks a week, cash through Zell every Friday, plus he'd give me a free iPad to use. I didn't even have to leave my dorm room. I said yes in, like, two seconds. The store was called Sunset Styles. Kevin sent me a drop box full of pictures. Crop tops, jeans, sneakers, dresses. All I had to do was post them with captions he wrote, schedule them for certain times, and answer DMs. Simple stuff. The first week, I got paid exactly on time. I remember buying groceries without checking my account first. Felt amazing. Then the messages started coming in. At first, just one or two people asking where their orders were. I'd forward the messages to Kevin like he told me. He'd say he'd handle it. But more kept coming. People were getting mad. One girl said she ordered a hoodie three weeks ago and got nothing. Another said the tracking number didn't work. I started feeling weird about it, but Kevin kept saying the shipping company messed up and he'd fix everything. By week three, my DMs were full of angry people. I'm talking hundreds of messages. People calling me a scammer, saying I stole their money. I tried talking to Kevin, but He just kept saying, forward it all to him and don't worry about it. He even gave me a script to copy paste. So sorry for the delay. Shipping is backed up, but your order is coming soon. I used that message probably 500 times, and this girl named Becca made a TikTok. She ordered a jacket for 60 bucks and never got it. But here's the thing. My face was in the Instagram stories. Kevin had me do a few try on videos to make the page look real. So Becca Screen recorded my videos and put them in her TikTok with text saying, this girl scammed me and won't respond. That video got a million views in two days. Suddenly, my Instagram was flooded. People found my personal account. They found my school. Someone posted a screenshot of me in the campus library with the caption, scammer goes here. My roommate came back one day and asked if I was actually stealing people's money. I tried explaining it wasn't me, but she looked at me like I was lying. I texted Kevin freaking out. I said I wanted to quit. He said I couldn't just quit because people were.

In this slow princess wave to the guests, stopping to smile at people. She's literally trying to have a bridal moment at my wedding. Some guests look confused. Others are whispering. But here's what none of them knew. Logan's groomsmen were my cousins. The same cousins who watched me get screwed over my entire childhood. The same ones who knew every single story of Brianna. I getting whatever she wanted while I got nothing. As Brianna reaches the halfway point, still waving and smiling, my cousin Dan and his brother set directly into the aisle in perfect sync. They pick her up horizontally like a surfboard. One guy has her shoulders, one has her legs. Brianna starts screaming, what are you doing? Put me down right now! They don't say a word. They just carry her straight past the shocked guests, out the side door and into the parking lot. Her bouquet falls on the ground. The entire church goes dead silent, and someone in the back starts clapping. Then more people join in. Then everyone's clapping and laughing. My parents jump up to chase after her, but my Aunt Helen physically blocks the exit. She's a big woman, and she plants herself there like a wall. She looks at them and says, sit down. You've ruined enough of her life. You're going to sit here and watch her get married. We finished the ceremony. It was perfect. Beautiful. Everything I wanted. During cocktail hour, I found out Brianna spent The entire reception, sitting in her car, crying because Dan stood guard at the door and told her if she tried to come back in, he'd call actual security to have her removed from property. My parents tried to apologize at the reception. I walked away mid sentence. They sent emails, texts, called Logan's parents to intervene and mediate. I blocked them and ignored everything for months. Six months later, they finally wrote a real apology letter, admitting they bailed me for decades and destroyed our relationship. They asked if we could start over and rebuild. I responded, maybe when you actually treat both your daughters equally. Until then, I'm done. Brianna never apologized. Last I heard, she's still telling people I humiliated her on purpose at my wedding. Good. She humiliated me for 25 years. Turn about is fair play.

You cared that much, you'd give up your seat and go sit with him in the back. But you want to keep your upgraded seat and have your kid up here? That's not my problem. That's when she lost it. Like, full on started wailing. Not crying, wailing. She's going, how could you do this to a child over and over again? People are staring. The flight attendant comes over, looking stressed. A woman sobbing now, telling the flight attendant I'm refusing to let her son sit with her. The flight attendant looks at me, and I just show her both boarding passes and explain I paid extra and offered to switch if she reimbursed me or moved to her own son's seat. The flight attendant's face changes. She tells the woman, ma'am, you can either take your assigned seat or switch with the passenger seated next to your son. We need to close the doors. The woman grabs her bag and storms off toward the back, still crying and muttering about how cruel people are these days. Like, two minutes later, this guy in his 20s sits down next to me, huge grin on his face. Dude, thank you so much. That kid would not stop kicking my seat during boarding, and his mom just kept saying, boys will be boys. Literally giddy about getting bumped up to Economy Plus for free. I thought it was over, but then my boyfriend text me after I land saying I was Too harsh. Apparently his mom thinks I should have just been nice and switched, because that's what good people do. And that I probably made that woman feel like a terrible mother.

I made a seat swapper cry. So I'm boarding this flight to visit my boyfriend's family for the first time. I saved up for three months to get an economy plus seat because I'm tall and regular economy makes my knees feel like they're gonna snap off. I get to my seat 12 A, throw my bag up top, and I'm literally just sitting down when this woman taps my shoulder. She's got this fake sweet smile on and goes, hi, would you mind switching seats with me? My son has really bad anxiety and he needs to sit with me. I look at her boarding pass. 32B. That's literally in the back of the plane, middle seat next to the bathroom. I paid an extra $70 for the seat. I'm like, oh, I actually paid for the seat, but I can switch if you reimburse me the $70 I spent on it. Her face goes red immediately. Are you seriously going to make a nine year old with anxiety sit alone? What kind of person are you? I'm confused now because, like, if her kid has such bad anxiety, why didn't she buy seats together? So I asked, wait, where are you sitting? 12C. She says, that's literally two seats over from me, also economy plus. So why don't you just trade seats with whoever sitting next to your son? Then you can sit with him. She crosses her arms. I need the leg room. I have back problems. I almost laughed. So you need the leg room, but your son with anxiety can just deal with sitting alone in the back. She starts getting loud. You're being incredibly selfish right now. He's a child, and you're his

I don't understand all these food restrictions nowadays. Finally, I just said, look, I have a medical condition. I can't eat gluten or I get really sick. I'm not being picky. I literally cannot digest it. His mom laughed and said, honey, that's just being a picky eater with extra steps. My generation didn't have all these made up allergies. I was so done at that point. I excused myself to the kitchen to start cleaning up, even though we weren't finished eating. When I came back 10 minutes later, they had eaten everything. Like everything. All the leftover chicken, all the potatoes, even the green beans, which they were complaining about earlier. My husband's plate was empty too. I just stood there staring at the empty dishes. I had barely eaten anything because I was so stressed from their comments. His mom notices me looking and goes, well, I guess it wasn't that bad after all. We were just hungry. Then she laughs like it's some big joke. I looked at my husband and he just shrugged, like literally just shrugged. Didn't say anything to defend me or acknowledge that this was messed up. So I grabbed my phone and ordered Thai food just for me. I got pad Thai, spring rolls, mango, sticky rice, the works, and like 40 bucks. When the delivery guy showed up, his parents were still there having coffee and cake that his mom brought. I answered the door, got my food and sat Down at the kitchen counter to eat it. His mom comes in and goes, what's all this? We just had dinner. I said, yeah, well, I didn't get to eat the dinner I spent three I was making because you guys finished it all while calling me a picky eater. I'm eating food that I can actually enjoy without being insulted. She got all huffy and said I was being dramatic. His dad tried to smooth things over by saying they didn't realise I hadn't eaten much. But his mom kept going, we didn't eat that much. And besides, if you made enough food, there would have been plenty for everyone. I just stared at her while eating my pad Thai. Then I said, you're right. Next time I'll make sure to cook enough food to feed people who complain about it the entire time and then eat all of it anyway. His mom's face went bright red and she started saying something about respect and how I was being rude in my own home. My husband finally spoke up and said, maybe we should all just calm down. His parents left pretty quickly after that.

My brother's wedding. I was handed a paper badge that read, limited access guest. My mom whispered, that means no plate. I looked over, walked to the gift table, retrieved my envelope with a 7,500 dollar fun check, and said, I think you won't need this anymore. Then I left. My brother ran after me, and my parents shouted, come back! The envelope sat there on the gift table, plain white, bent at the corner. Inside was a 7,500 dollar check I'd saved for months. Extra shifts, vacations, saying no to things I wanted. All of it. I told Ryan weeks earlier I had something big planned. He'd called me late one night, voice tight, saying, Mel, I don't know how we're going to afford the honeymoon. I said, don't worry, I've got you. At the reception, check in. The woman handed me a paper badge. Not gold trimmed like everyone else's, just white, flimsy, printed in thick black. Limited access guest. My mom appeared beside me. That means no plate, she whispered, then walked off before I could respond. I checked the seating chart. My name wasn't listed. Not at the family table, not anywhere. I wasn't a guest. I was a placeholder they forgot to remove. I'd driven two hours to get here, bought a new dress, taken the day off work. All of it for nothing. I stood near the wall, watching Ryan toast, watching my parents clap, watching everyone settle in. My aunt was laughing at Something someone said. My cousins were taking selfies at their table. They saw me. They just didn't care. So I walked back to the gift table, opened my envelope, pulled out the check, and said, loud enough, I think you won't need this anymore. Chairs scraped. Someone shouted my name. Ryan's voice, then my parents, both yelling, come back! Come back! I didn't. I drove home and didn't sleep. Not from anger, but because I kept seeing that paper badge in my hands. By morning, the text started. Can we talk? Please don't make this a thing. No apologies, just deflection. My mom wrote, we assumed you'd be okay with standing, since you always say you don't care about fancy stuff. My dad called. I ignored him. Then he texted, come over, we want to talk. Your brother's here, too. I went, not to fix anything, just to watch them squirm. They were all in the living room when I arrived. My dad said it was unfortunate how things went. My mom used the word oversight three times. Ryan barely spoke. When he did, he said, I didn't know it would be like that. I thought you'd understand. I let them finish. Then I said I might change my mind.

Room shifted instantly. My mom sat up, eyes wide. My dad exhaled relief. Ryan finally looked at me. My mom started talking fast about how the money would go to the honeymoon, how she didn't want this little thing to hang over us. My dad chimed in about families getting through rough moments. I stood. I need time to think. I left them with that word, my buzzing in their ears. For once, they wanted something from me. Three days later, my mom called. They were delaying the honeymoon. No check, no trip. That's when I remembered. I'd loaned them my second car six months ago. It was still in my name, still on my insurance. They'd said it was temporary, a week or two while theirs was in the shop. That was in March. It was now September. I scheduled a tow for Friday morning. 9 12 a m, my phone rang. My mom, there's someone outside towing the car. Did you do this? Yes. I said, silence. Why? I'm changing insurance companies. She said they needed the car. I said, then maybe you should rent one. That's what I'd have to do, right? This is about the wedding, isn't it? No. I said, this is about patterns. I hung up. That afternoon, a text from someone I didn't know. This is Kiara's cousin. I helped organize the wedding. You were originally listed as family. Full access, seated with your parents and Ryan. Three days before the wedding, your Mom changed it. She emailed a revised list. Ryan approved it. I remember thinking it felt wrong, but I figured it was a family thing. They knew Ryan saw my name on the original list and let them move me. They wanted the envelope, not me. I deleted the family group chat, blocked my parents, muted Ryan's number. Two days later, my dad tried again. Family is complicated. We all make mistakes. We love you. No apology, just excuses. I didn't reply. I opened the file labeled loan terms and deleted it. A week later, Ryan's fiance texted. I don't know what happened, but I still think you did the right thing. I replied, thank you. Two months later, Ryan sent one message. I miss you. I read it. Then I blocked his number. They didn't lose a daughter. They lost access to my generosity.

Sorry to interrupt. I just have something everyone should hear. Before the wedding, I connected my phone to the Bluetooth speaker. Thank you. Saved password and hit play. Rebecca's voice filled the yard. He's sweet, but boring. Once we get the house sold, we can finally be together for real. Silence, then gasps. A glass shattered. Rebecca's face drained. That's not what it sounds like. Oh, it's exactly what it sounds like. I held up printed photos. Her and Bradley at the Marriott. Her mom's hand went to her mouth. You've been sleeping with your lawyer and plotting to sell my house. Proof, time stamps, audio, everything. Rebecca screamed. You hired someone to follow me? That's illegal. Recording a fraud scheme. Totally legal. Her sister Nicole muttered, Becca, what the hell? Rebecca snapped, shut up! Tom's loaded. He can afford it. That house is half mine anyway. Eight months, I said. You've lived there eight months, paid zero rent, contributed nothing. You don't own a brick. I pulled out an envelope. You've been served eviction notice. Got 30 days to get out. Your things are already packed. Dennis and Mike are loading the truck right now. Storage unit on Riverside. First month's on me. She lunged at me. Her mom and sister had to grab her. You can't do this. We're engaged. Not anymore. I said calmly. Weddings canceled. Venue vendors all notified an hour ago. And Bradley's wife? She got copies of everything. That shut her up. Her mom, Started crying. Guests gathered. Someone yelled, holy shit! As I walked out. By the time I got home, Rebecca's ring was on the dresser. The PI texted, Bradley's wife just called his office. He's finished. I poured a drink, opened my blinds, and watched the movers haul her boxes away. That's how I ended an engagement, exposed two frauds, and kept my house. All in one afternoon.

Letters, thinking I'd be homeless. Those nights flooded back. Crying alone at 2 a m. The shame of thinking I'd messed up. The fear of calling my parents to admit I was failing. And you knew. I continued. You watched me fall apart and told me they were mistakes. You promised you'd handle it. Kira blew on her nails, looking bored. I was going to fix it eventually. Eventually, I screamed. I'm getting kicked out in three days. She rolled her eyes. You're being dramatic. Just ask your parents for money. That's when I noticed the gold bracelet on her wrist. Delicate and expensive. My rent money turned into jewelry. I called the landlord right there. I'm filing a police report, I said. Kira stole my rent payments. I have Venmo proof. My landlord's voice turned serious. Come to my office tomorrow morning with your records. Bring your roommate. Kira jumped up, knocking over the Polish bottle. Pink liquid spread across the carpet. You're seriously calling the cops? You stole $2,550 from me and almost destroyed my future, I said coldly. What did you expect? The next morning, we sat in my landlord's office. Kira's parents were on speaker phone. Her mother was crying. She'll pay everything back. Her father said. Please don't call the police. My landlord wouldn't back down. Your daughter committed theft and almost cost my tenant her education. I'm ending her lease immediately. She has 48 hours to leave. Kira was crying, mascara running down her Face in black streaks, but I felt nothing except cold relief. She lost her apartment that week, but I kept her designer bags. I never spoke to her again.

I drove home 15 over the limit. When I opened the door, Kira was on the couch painting her toenails bright pink. A green face mask covered her face, and cucumber slices sat on a plate beside her. We need to talk right now, I said. She didn't look up. Can it wait? This polish takes forever to dry, the landlord said. I'm three months behind on rent, she said. You pay your part on time, but I've been sending you $850 every month. Kira's hand froze. Pink polish dripped onto the carpet. Oh my god, I totally forgot to forward it, she said casually, still focused on her toes. I've been so busy with my Instagram. I'll send it right now. Forgot for three months? My voice cracked. That's $2,550. I'm getting kicked out Friday, losing my scholarship and having to quit school. She sighed. Like I was being annoying. It's not that serious. I had expenses come up. I was going to pay it back eventually. That's when I saw the shopping bags behind the couch. Three bags with designer logos from stores I'd never entered. What expenses? Those bags. Your Miami trip last month. Kira shrugged and went back to her nails. I needed a mental health break. College is stressful. My hands clenched into fists. I've been eating ramen for every meal. I skipped my best friend's birthday because I couldn't afford it. I had panic attacks over those letters, thinking I'd be homeless those nights. Flooded back crying. Alone at 2 a m. The shame of thinking I'd messed up. The fear of calling my parents to admit I was failing. And you knew. I continued. You watched me fall apart and told me they were mistakes. You promised you'd handle it. Kira blew on her nails, looking bored.

How do you know that? She blinked. Oh, you mentioned it. No, I didn't. I hired a private investigator the next morning. Three days later, he called. You might want to sit down. Bradley isn't just her lawyer friend. They've been meeting at hotels twice a week for four months. He sent photos, Marriott, his car, his apartment. Dates going back to before the prenup talk. Then the kicker. Bradley's deep in debt. Specializes in partition sales, forcing co owners to sell property. Their plan was simple. She gets on my deed, they force a sale, split the profit. My fiance and her side piece lawyer were trying to steal my house. Her bridal shower was in two weeks. 40 guests, mom hosting. I smiled for the first time in days. I played perfect. Fiance attended tastings, smiled for photos, even met Bradley for paperwork. He reeked of Cologne and arrogance. No rush, buddy, he said, smirking. Sooner's better for tax purposes. Sure, pal. The PI kept sending proof. Audio this time. Rebecca laughing in Bradley's car. He's sweet, but boring. Once we sell the house, we can finally be together for real. That was my green light. Bridal shower, day two PM. Packed backyard. Champagne and gold decorations everywhere. Rebecca and a tiara opening gifts. Mom answered the door. Tom, what are you doing here? It's bad luck. Need a quick word with the bride. I walked straight to the center of the party. Every woman turned. Sorry to Interrupt. I just have something everyone should hear before the wedding. I connected my phone to the Bluetooth speaker. Thank you. Saved password and hit play. Rebecca's voice filled the yard. He's sweet, but boring. Once we get the house sold, we can finally be together for real. Silence, then gasps. A glass shattered Rebecca's face.
NA

My landlord found me at a coffee shop and said, you're three months behind on rent. I have to start eviction by Friday if you don't pay the $2,550 you owe. I froze because that made no sense. Kind. I pay every month. My scholarship required stable housing within five miles of campus, which meant eviction would cost me my financial aid and force me to drop out completely. I pulled out my phone with shaking hands. Look. $850 on the first of every month. September, October, November. My landlord squinted at my screen. Why are you sending money to Kira? You both pay me separately. I looked at him all confused. Kira said it would be easier if I sent her my half and she'd bundle both payments together. He shook his head. I never agreed to that. Kira pays her part on time every month. But I haven't gotten a dollar from you since August. My heart rate went up, and it wasn't because of the caffeine. I'd worked two jobs to never miss a payment for this room. The eviction letters, I whispered. Kira said they were billing mistakes. She told me she'd handle it. My landlord shook his head. Those definitely weren't mistakes. No payment by Friday means I have to file eviction papers. Three months times $850. I had pocketed $2,550 and never sent a cent to the landlord. My coffee spilled as I stood up, but I didn't care. I drove home 15 over The limit. When I opened the door, Kira was on the couch painting her toenails bright pink. voice_to_text: At dinner I said, can't wait for the family reunion. My brother laughed. You're not invited. It's for real family. Everyone laughed. I just smiled and left. Four days later, my dad tried to withdraw 20 four hundred dollars. I sent a screenshot. Payment denied. Must be that family only policy. Two days later, I heard a loud knock on my door. I've been the one who found the cabin, confirmed dates and sent the deposit. Weeks went by. Group chat went quiet. I asked twice if we were still going. Nobody answered. That night at dinner, everyone acted normal. Halfway through, I brought it up, so when's the reunion happening? But he looked me straight in the eye. You're not invited. It's for real family. The table erupted full on shoulders, moving laughter. Lana smiled and looked down. Mom kept chewing. Dad snorted. I smiled too, not because it was funny, but because I finally understood who they were. I stood up, folded my napkin and walked out. Four days later, dad tried pulling $2,400 from the joint emergency account I'd opened three years ago when Mom's hospital bills started piling up. The withdrawal was declined. I was the only one contributing. They used it for car repairs, Lana's textbooks, Cody's rent. Never said thank you. Two days later, heavy pounding on my door at 8:00am. Through the people, dad, mom and Cody. I opened the door just wide enough. What is this about freezing the account? I kept My voice calm. The accounts in my name. I put the money in. You weren't entitled to it. It's family money. That's not what I heard at dinner. You actually took that seriously. It was a joke. Nobody corrected you. You all laughed then stayed silent when I left. Get over yourself. You can get over the canceled vacation. Mom's face paled. Canceled. Charged back the deposit. I booked it. I paid for it. It's gone. Dad, explode. I made every call, paid the down payment, did all the work while you plan to cut me out. I turned to mom. Remember your emergency dental work last year? I covered that. Quietly, she nodded slowly. The hospital co pays the car insurance, your medications, all me. Dad, panic flashed across his face. And mom. The credit card you opened in my name three years ago, I paid it off, but not the.

Need or make someone smile during the holidays. That's Santa's magic working through them. His mom started crying. Other parents nodded approvingly. The kid smiled and asked if he could help be Santa's magic, too. I gave him two candy canes and told him to give one to someone who looked like they needed cheering up. By closing time, word had spread about Steve Claus. The mall manager asked if I could come back tomorrow. Parents were specifically requesting Santa's brother. Brenda offered me $500 for the week. My girlfriend found me still in costume, surrounded by children and took about 50 photos while laughing hysterically. I worked that entire week as claws. Kids would bring drawings of what they imagine the whole claws family look like. One boy brought cookies specifically for me, not Santa. A girl gave me a handmade business card that said assistant to make my job sound more official. On Christmas Eve, my last shift, the original Santa showed up. He'd heard about Steve Claus and came to see what the fuss was about. We took a photo together, told kids we were heading back to help Santa with a big night. The crowd applauded. That mall still has a Steve Claus every year now. It became their thing. I set the precedent, and now some other bearded guy continues the tradition. Last week, a teenager recognized me at a coffee shop. You're the original Steve Claus, he said. Turns out he was Tyler the Kid who exposed me that first day, he said that Christmas was his favorite because he got to be part of creating a new legend.

Children started crying. Brenda looked like she might faint. That's when inspiration struck. I leaned forward and whispered loudly enough for everyone to hear, you're absolutely right, Tyler. I'm not Santa! The crowd gasped. Brenda's face went white, but I continued. I'm Santa's brother, Steve. Santa's busy at the North Pole with a massive toy emergency. A whole shipment of game consoles got delivered to the wrong warehouse. I need to take notes on what everyone wants while he fixes it. Tyler's eyes widened. Santa has a brother? I nodded solemnly. Someone has to run the workshop while he's delivering presents. I usually stay at the North Pole, but this is an emergency. Line of children buzzed with excitement. They'd met Santa's brother. This was even better than regular Santa. For the next three hours, I became Steve Claus. I told kids about my workshop specializing in unusual toys. I explained how I invented the self wrapping present. One girl asked why I wasn't famous like Santa, and I said I preferred working behind the scenes. Some. No one has to test all those video games. I winked. Parents started taking pictures, posting about meeting Santa's mysterious brother. Kids asked increasingly creative questions, and I made up an entire Claus family history. There was Uncle Pete, who trained the reindeer, Cousin Maria, who designed the slay's GPS system, and Grandma Claus, who quality tested all the cookies. Around hour four, a kid with thick glasses approached. My dad says Santa isn't real. He said quietly. The crowd went silent. This was the moment every mall Santa dreaded. I knelt down to his level. Your dad's right about something, I said. The Santa you see in stores and malls isn't the real one. But that doesn't mean the magic isn't real. Every time someone gives a gift, helps someone in

Have you ever been recruited to be Santa's helper at a mall by a desperate elf? Last December I was killing time at the mall, waiting for my girlfriend to finish her shift at the jewelry store, when a tiny woman in an elf costume grabbed my arm. you have to help me, she whispered, her fake pointed ears drooping. Santa just quit mid shift and there are 40 kids in line. I'm 6 foot 4 with a beard I've been growing since October. She looked at me like I was the answer to her prayers. I don't know anything about being Santa, I protested. She was already dragging me toward the North Pole setup. Can you say ho ho, ho and not swear in front of children? When I nodded, she said, you're hired. Before I could object, she shoved me into a break room where a red suit hung on a chair, still warm from the previous Santa. He left because the kid threw up on him, she explained, tossing me the pants. Third time this week. I should have run, but she looked so desperate, and somewhere outside, children were waiting. The suit was too small, the jacket barely closed, the pants ended at my calves, and the beard kept sliding sideways. The elf, who introduced herself as Brenda, looked me over and sighed. It'll have to do. Just remember, every kid gets a candy cane, no promises about specific gifts, and absolutely no holding babies. My first kid was easy. A shy five year old who whispered she wanted a Dinosaur. I deepened my voice, said something about checking my list, and sent her off with a candy cane. I thought I had this figured out. Then came Tyler. Tyler was seven, tactical, and armed with questions. Why does your beard smell like coffee? He demanded. How do you fit down chimneys if you're so fat? Before I could answer, he pulled my beard down and announced to the entire line, this isn't the real Santa. Panic spread through the crowd. Parents glared.

What small gesture meant the world to you? When I was 14, I'd already figured out how life worked. You don't expect anything from anyone, and you don't get disappointed. Simple math. My dad left when I was, like, two. I don't even remember his face. My mom was around, technically, but most nights she'd be knocked out on the couch with a bottle next to her, and I'd just make myself ramen or whatever we had left in the cupboard. At school, I was basically furniture. Not bullied, not popular. Just there. I'd sit in the back, do my work, go home, repeat. I had this one hoodie I wore almost every day because it had big pockets and I could just disappear into it. Teachers knew my name, but that was about it. I was the kid who turned in assignments on time and never caused problems, so nobody really looked twice. My birthday that year was on a Tuesday. I woke up, got dressed, went to school. My mom didn't say anything because she probably didn't even know what day it was. I didn't tell anyone because what was the point? At lunch, I sat alone like always, eating the free meal they gave out. And I just thought about how this was my 14th birthday. And it felt exactly like a random Wednesday in March. Then in homeroom that morning, Miss Harmon called me over to her desk. She taught English, and I had her for Third period. But homeroom was just where they took attendance and made announcements. I walked up, thinking maybe I forgot to turn something in or messed up a paper. She had this little white box on her desk, wrapped in shiny blue paper with a silver ribbon. Hey, I think this is yours, she I said, holding it out. I just stared at it. What? It's for you. Open it. My hands were shaking a little when I took it. I didn't understand what was happening. The wrapping paper made that crinkling sound when I tore it, and inside was this tiny silver necklace with a heart charm. It wasn't fancy. Probably cost like 10 bucks at the mall, but I looked at it like someone just handed me a bar of gold. I heard you mentioned last week your birthday was coming up, Miss Harmon said, smiling. Figured you should have something to Mark the day. I don't even remember telling anyone my birthday. Maybe I said it to someone in passing or wrote it on.

Everyone to hear. Hey, Uncle Tommy, tell everyone that funny story about when you got so drunk at your son's graduation you tried to give a speech and ended up barfing on the principal's shoes. That was hilarious, right? Your son still won't talk to you, but at least you got a funny story out of it. My mom covered her mouth trying not to laugh, and my dad had to look away. At New Year's, when he tried to make a toast, I jumped up first. Let me tell a joke first. What do you call a guy who's been divorced three times, lost every business he started, and still gives relationship and financial advice? Uncle Tommy. Get it? Because it's funny how he thinks anyone should listen to him. Uncle Tommy finally lost it. You think you're so funny, don't you? He screamed at me while spit flew out of his mouth, making jokes about my divorces and my mistakes like you're some kind of comedian. It's not funny. It's just mean and disrespectful. I smiled at him, real calm. But, Uncle Tommy, you said if we can't laugh at ourselves, we'll never make it in life. I'm just helping you laugh at yourself. Why is it suddenly not funny when the jokes are about you? The whole room went dead silent, and Uncle Tommy's face looked like it might explode. Remember when you made my sister cry about her weight at her graduation? I kept going. Or that Super funny bit where you told Kim's kids their dad was too stupid to get a real job. Was that funny, Uncle Tommy? My mom stood up and crossed her arms. Yeah, Tommy, explain to us why your jokes are funny but his aren't. Uncle Tommy tried to say I was attacking him, but my dad said, now you know how your jokes feel to everyone else. Maybe you should think about. Uncle Tommy sat back down and didn't make any more mean jokes. But when he went for dessert, I said, that's your third piece of pie, Uncle Tommy. It's a good thing your new girlfriend doesn't care about your dad bought as long as you have money. Uncle Tommy just put his head down and pushed his plate away.

I started roasting my uncle at every family gathering until he cried on Thanksgiving. Uncle Tommy walked through the door and immediately came over to where I was practicing piano. Still wasting your parents money on those piano lessons? He said. Hey, everyone, listen to this. It sounds like someone's torturing a bunch of sick geese while they're trying to sing the national anthem. Oh, wait, that's just my nephew playing piano. Everyone laughed nervously, and I turned around on the bench. Uncle Tommy, that's really mean. I've been practicing for months. Could you please stop? He rolled his eyes at me. Don't be such a baby. It's just a joke. If you can't laugh at yourself, you'll never make it in life, kiddo. Then he walked over to my cousin Kim, who just got engaged last month. Hey, everyone, wanna start a betting pool? He was grinning. I give this marriage six months, tops. We all know how desperate Kim was to find anyone who would marry her. Kim's face went bright red, and her fiance looked like he wanted to leave right then. Uncle Tommy kept going, pointing at my sister. Speaking of desperation, here's our family teacher. You know what's funny about teachers? They get paid in crayon drawings and apple juice because that's all they're worth. He laughed at his own joke. At least the kids in your class have someone at their level to relate to, right? My sister ran out of the room. My Grandpa laughed. Kids really are too sensitive. Tommy's just joking around. My aunt nodded and added, it's just his sense of humor. You all need to learn to take a joke. By the time dinner was over, Kim had left early and my sister wouldn't come out of her room. At Christmas, I came ready with my own jokes about Uncle Tommy's life. He walked in wearing another expensive suit, and I announced to everyone, hey, look, everyone! Uncle Tommy wore his fancy suit! You know, the one he bought before his third wife took everything, including his house and his last bit of self respect. His eye twitched, but he laughed it off. Have you ever been mistaken for a celebrity's bodyguard at a Buffalo Wild Wings? Last month I stopped at Buffalo Wild Wings after my kickboxing class. I was wearing all black compression pants, a tank top, and I hadn't showered yet. My hair was in a tight bun, and I probably looked intimidating. Whatever. I just wanted boneless wings. I'm sitting at the bar, scrolling through my phone when this guy in designer sunglasses and a baseball cap walks in. He's got that trying not to be noticed vibe that actually makes you more noticeable. He sits two seats away from me, orders a beer, and keeps glancing around nervously. Then a group of college kids spots him. One girl gasps loudly and whispers to her friends there, all staring and pulling out phones. The guy tenses up. That's when one of the girls approaches me instead of him. Excuse me, can we get a photo with him? We'll be super quick. I blink. With who? She gestures toward the guy. We know you're working, but we're huge fans. Just one picture? Oh. Oh, no. She thinks I'm his bodyguard. The guy is watching this interaction with growing panic. Before I can correct her, he gives me this desperate, pleading look. For some inexplicable reason, I make a split second decision to play along. He's off duty right now, I say in my most authoritative voice. He's trying to enjoy a private meal. The girl's face falls. We understand. Sorry. To bother you. She returns to her table, and they're all whispering excitedly about how he has a bodyguard. The guy visibly relaxes. He leans over slightly. Thank you so much. I'm sorry for dragging you into this.
